content:
### CSS Z-Index

**z-index** controls the stacking order of overlapping elements.

---

### How It Works

```css
.element {
  position: relative;
  z-index: 10;  /* Higher value = on top */
}
```

Elements with higher `z-index` appear in front of those with lower values.

---

### Only Works on Positioned Elements

`z-index` only affects elements with a `position` value other than `static`:

```css
/* Works */
z-index: 10; /* position: relative/absolute/fixed/sticky required */

/* Does NOT work */
position: static;
z-index: 10; /* Ignored! */
```

---

### Stacking Context

A **stacking context** is a group of elements that stack together:

| Creates Stacking Context | Example |
|-------------------------|---------|
| Root element | `<html>` |
| Positioned + z-index | `position: relative; z-index: 1` |
| Opacity < 1 | `opacity: 0.9` |
| Transform | `transform: scale(1)` |
| Filter | `filter: blur(0)` |
| Will-change | `will-change: transform` |
| Container queries | `container-type: inline-size` |

Elements in one stacking context cannot interleave with another.

---

### Default Values

| Value | Stack Level |
|-------|-------------|
| `auto` | Same as parent (default) |
| `0` | Base layer in stacking context |
| `1` | Above base |
| `-1` | Below base |
| `9999` | Very high (use sparingly) |

---

### Common Patterns

```css
/* Overlay */
.overlay {
  position: fixed;
  inset: 0;
  background: rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
  z-index: 100;
}

/* Modal on top of overlay */
.modal {
  position: fixed;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  z-index: 200;
}

/* Dropdown above content */
.dropdown {
  position: absolute;
  top: 100%;
  z-index: 50;
}
```

---

### Z-Index Best Practices

- Use small increments (1, 10, 100)
- Avoid values above 100 except for overlays/modals
- Group related elements:
  ```css
  /* Content: 1-9 */
  /* Header: 10 */
  /* Dropdowns: 50 */
  /* Overlay: 100 */
  /* Modal: 200 */
  /* Toast: 300 */
  ```

> **Key Point:** `z-index` is relative to its stacking context. A child with `z-index: 9999` inside a parent with `z-index: 1` will still be behind a sibling with `z-index: 2`.
